The Department of Classics is pleased to host Professor James Uden, Professor of Classical Studies at Boston University, as the 2025 McKibben Lecturer. Professor Uden will give a talk entitled “Love in a Time of Bankruptcy: Calculations in Catullus.”


In one of the most famous poems in Latin literature, Catullus urges his beloved Lesbia to give him a thousand kisses, then a hundred, then a thousand, then another hundred… and then tells her that they will ‘confuse the score,’ so onlookers will not know how many times they kissed. Why? Latin students learn that the verb ‘confuse the score’ (conturbabimus) is drawn from the language of accounting. But why would Catullus introduce a reference to economic calculation during a passionate address to a lover? In this lecture, I show that Catullus’ love language is shaped by a keen awareness of Rome’s economic problems in the 50s BCE – of political leaders risking it all in pursuing their ambitions and consuls teetering on the edge of bankruptcy. The impulsive lover begging for kisses and the frantic politician deep in debt turns out to have more in common than may first appear.&#160;


All are welcome. A reception to honor Professor Uden will follow the lecture.

